pr_review_comment_body:
@tobes This is new. We standardize things. Ought to decide if we want `req_timeout` (this), `negative_cache_timeout` (whatismyip), `request_timeout` (pingdom, weather_yahoo, exchange_rate, github), `http_timeout` (graphite), `modem_timeout` (wwan ; not exactly same), `timeout` (rt, getjson, glpi), `HARDCODED TIMEOUT` in some modules (exchange_rate, rss_aggregator), etc.

Maybe we can take care of this option in same way we do with `color_*`?
One `request_timeout = 10 (default)` to rule them all.

@davvid Alright then, I'll do it :)

Another minor thing I've noticed -- have you considered replacing the boilerplate in `jsonpickle.compat` with `six` so you don't have to reinvent the wheel? (as recommended in the official python docs --https://docs.python.org/3/howto/pyporting.html#drop-support-for-python-2-5-and-older-at-least). It's a slim requirement and the chances are most users already have it installed due to it being a very common dependency.

Otherwise, we'll have to add even more unneeded copy/paste style boilerplate to `compat` in order to have proper metaclass unit tests in both python 2/3... It also provides things like `six.class_types`, `six.get_unbound_method` which are done differently in 2/3 and could be handy here.

Suppose you define an enum inside a message like this:

```
message Test {
    enum test_enum {
        TEST_ENUM_FIELD_1 = 1;
    }
}
```

In Google's protobuf, the `Test` class will have a class-level attribute called `TEST_ENUM_FIELD_1` with the integer value 1. This macro replicates that behaviour in pyrobuf.

```py
if not response['files']:
```

Instead of using the `<b>` tag here, remove it, and bold this paragraph in the CSS. Like this:
```css
#summary-host {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```
By only using CSS to style, we separate style from content.
